Chapter 4 Multivariate normal distributions¶

Normal distributions for more than 1 variable.

Review: Univariate normal distributions

A theoretical model --- a normal distribution happens to describe this bell-shaped pattern very well. Variables such as human height, IQ scores, repeated measurements of a same object, body temperature are approximately normally distributed.

A random variable follows a normal distribution if its probability density has the form

$$ f(x) = \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt {2 \pi} } e^{-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2 \sigma^2}} $$

$\mu$: the mean

$\sigma $: the standard deviation.

Standard normal distribution is a normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

$Z$: A standard normal random variable.

Question: a) plot the probability density curve for a standard normal distribution.

      b) plot the probability density curve for a normal distribution with a mean of 3.2 and the standard deviation of 7.1.

Outliers: $3 \sigma$ criteria for outliers.

$99.7\%$ of data fall within 3 standard deviations of the mean for a normal distribution.

Normality check¶

If we would like to see if the data are from a normal distribution or not, we can run normlity check.

  1. Histogram / boxplot

  2. Normality tests

  3. QQ normal plot

A QQ (Quantile-Quantile) normal plot is a graphical tool used to assess if a given dataset follows a normal distribution. It is a useful visual tool for checking assumptions about the distribution of data in data analysis. If the points in a QQ normal plot fall approximately along a line, it suggests that the data is normally distributed approximately. If the points deviate from the line, it indicates that the data may not follow a normal distribution.

Multivariate normal distributions¶

A multivariate normal distribution is the generalization of the univariate normal (bell curve) to multiple dimensions. Instead of describing a single random variable, it describes a vector of random variables that may be correlated with each other.

A $p$-dimensional random vector $\mathbf{X}$ has a multivariate normal distribution with a mean vector $\mathbf{\mu}$ and variance-covariance matrix $\Sigma$:

$$ \phi(\textbf{x})=\left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^{p/2}|\Sigma|^{-1/2}\exp\{-\frac{1}{2}(\textbf{x}-\mathbf{\mu})'\Sigma^{-1}(\textbf{x}-\mathbf{\mu})\} $$$$ \mathbf{X} \sim N(\mathbf{\mu},\Sigma) $$

A bivariate normal: $$ \left(\begin{array}{c}X_1\\X_2 \end{array}\right) \sim N \left[\left(\begin{array}{c}\mu_1\\ \mu_2 \end{array}\right), \left(\begin{array}{cc}\sigma^2_1 & \rho \sigma_1\sigma_2 \\ \rho\sigma_1\sigma_2 & \sigma^2_2 \end{array}\right)\right] $$

Key Properties¶

  1. Marginals:
    Any subset of components of $\mathbf{X}$ also follows a multivariate normal distribution.

  2. Linearity:
    Any linear combination $a^T \mathbf{X}$ is univariate normal.

  3. Independence & Zero Correlation:
    In a multivariate normal, uncorrelated variables are also independent (which is not true in general distributions).

  4. Geometry:
    Contours of equal probability density are ellipsoids, shaped by $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$.

Applications in Statistics and Machine Learning¶

The multivariate normal distribution is the foundation for much of multivariate statistics because:

  • Foundation for classical methods
    Many inferential procedures in multivariate statistics assume MVN:

    • Hotellings $T^2$ test (multivariate generalization of the $t$-test)
    • MANOVA (multivariate analysis of variance)
    • Discriminant analysis
    • Factor analysis
    • Principal component analysis (PCA) often assumes MVN to derive statistical properties.

  • Generative models:
    Gaussian Mixture Models (GMMs) use MVNs to model complex data distributions.

$$ p(\mathbf{x}) = \sum_{k=1}^K \pi_k \, \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{x} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu}_k, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_k), $$

where

  • $\pi_k$ = mixing coefficient for component $k$, with $\pi_k \geq 0$ and $\sum_{k=1}^K \pi_k = 1$,
  • $\boldsymbol{\mu}_k$ = mean vector of the $k$-th Gaussian,
  • $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_k$ = covariance matrix of the $k$-th Gaussian,
  • $\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{x} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu}_k, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_k)$ = PDF of a multivariate normal distribution:
$$ \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{x} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}) = \frac{1}{(2\pi)^{d/2} |\boldsymbol{\Sigma}|^{1/2}} \exp \!\left( -\tfrac{1}{2} (\mathbf{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})^T \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} (\mathbf{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu}) \right). $$

  • Classification:
    Linear/Quadratic Discriminant Analysis assume class-conditional MVNs.

  • Dimensionality reduction:
    Principal Component Analysis (PCA) relies on the covariance structure of an MVN.

  • Bayesian inference:
    Conjugate priors (normal-inverse-Wishart) simplify updates for Gaussian likelihoods.

  • Gaussian processes:
    Define distributions over functions using MVN properties.

  • Kalman filters:
    State-space models assume Gaussian noise for sequential prediction.

$$ C = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix} $$
In [17]:
library(mvtnorm)

mean.vec = c(2,6)
cmat = matrix( c(2,-1,-1,2), nrow = 2)

#Define a range of (x1, x2) for the plot

x1 = seq( -2, 6, length = 200  )
x2 = seq( 2, 10, length = 200  )

#multivariate normal probability density dmvnorm(cbind(x, y), mu, sigma0)

f = function(x, y) dmvnorm(cbind(x, y), mean.vec, cmat)
#calcualtion all points (x1, x2) in the grid
z = outer(x1, x2, f)
#A contour plot

#3d perspective plot
persp(x1, x2, z, theta = 30, phi = 15)

#Contour plot 
#z : the value of the bivariate function over x1, x2
contour(x1, x2, z)

Confidence Intervals/Regions¶

A confidence interval for a population parameter is a range (region) to caputure the unknown population parameter with a certain level of confidence.

For example : a 90% confidence interval for the population mean of variable " Alar_extent", that is, we are 90% sure that the population mean of variable " Alar_extent" is in the interval. A confidence interval is an interval in the number line.

A 95% confidence region for the population mean vector of "Total_length " and "Alar_extent": we are 95% confidence that the the population mean vector of "Total_length " and "Alar_extent" fall in the region.

A confidence region is a multi-dimensional generalization of a confidence interval.

$$(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol\mu)^T\boldsymbol\Sigma^{-1}(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol\mu)\le \chi_{p,\alpha}^2 \tag{1}$$

Example: Construct a 95% confidence interval for the population mean of Alar_extent. Please interpret it.

Normality check for multivariate data¶

To check if several variables follow a multivariate normal distribution or not.

Multivariate QQ normal plot instead of using a univariate QQ normal plot multiple times. That each of all individual variables has a normal distribution does not imply multivariate normal of all these variables.

Example: construct a multivariate QQ normal plot to check if all quantative variables in the data are from a joint multivariate normal distribution.¶

Since all the points in the QQ normal plot roughly follow a straight line pattern, the data (the quantitatvie varaibles of the sparrow data) are form a multivariate normal approximately.

For high dimensional data , p (the number of variables) is not small (even large) compared to the sample size (n), we may be careful.

Linear Transformation of a Multivariate Normal¶

Temperature data (x) in Celsis to Fairenheit: y = 9/5 x + 32

Let a $p$-dimensional random vector be

$$ \mathbf{X}_i = \begin{pmatrix} X_{i1} \\ X_{i2} \\ \vdots \\ X_{ip} \end{pmatrix}. $$

A linear combination of the components is

$$ Y = c_1 X_1 + c_2 X_2 + \dots + c_p X_p = \sum_{j=1}^p c_j X_j = \mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{X}, $$

where $\mathbf{c} = (c_1, c_2, \dots, c_p)^T$ is a vector of constants.
More generally, a linear transformation is given by

$$ A \mathbf{X}_i, $$

where $A$ is a $k \times p$ matrix.

1. Mean of a Linear Combination¶

The expectation of $Y = \mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{X}$ is

$$ E(Y) = \sum_{j=1}^p c_j E(X_j) = \mathbf{c}^T \mu, $$

where $\mu = E(\mathbf{X})$ is the mean vector of $\mathbf{X}$.

Thus, the mean of a linear combination is simply the linear combination of the individual means.

2. Variance of a Linear Combination¶

The variance of $Y$ is

$$ \begin{aligned} Var(Y) &= Var\!\left(\sum_{j=1}^p c_j X_j \right) \\[6pt] &= Cov\!\left(\sum_{i=1}^p c_i X_i,\; \sum_{j=1}^p c_j X_j \right) \\[6pt] &= \sum_{i=1}^p \sum_{j=1}^p c_i c_j \, Cov(X_i, X_j) \\[6pt] &= \mathbf{c}^T \Sigma \mathbf{c}, \end{aligned} $$

where $\Sigma = Cov(\mathbf{X})$ is the covariance matrix.

3. Extension: Linear Transformation with a Matrix¶

For a general matrix $A$ and random vector $\mathbf{X}$, define

$$ \mathbf{Y} = A \mathbf{X}. $$

  • The mean vector of $\mathbf{Y}$ is
    $$ E(\mathbf{Y}) = A \, E(\mathbf{X}) = A \mu. $$

  • The covariance matrix of $\mathbf{Y}$ is
    $$ Cov(\mathbf{Y}) = A \, \Sigma \, A^T. $$

Summary¶

  • Linear combinations of multivariate normal random vectors are also normal.
  • The mean and variance follow from the properties of expectation and covariance:
    • $E(\mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{X}) = \mathbf{c}^T \mu$
    • $Var(\mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{X}) = \mathbf{c}^T \Sigma \mathbf{c}$
  • For a general transformation $A \mathbf{X}$:
    • $E(A \mathbf{X}) = A \mu$
    • $Cov(A \mathbf{X}) = A \Sigma A^T$

Example: Suppose that we are interested in the difference between the 0-day and the 4-day measurements. What is the distribution? Please plot the distribution.

Suppose that

  • $X_1$: 0-day measurement
  • $X_2$: 2-day measurement
  • $X_3$: 4-day measurement

and $\mathbf{X} = (X_1, X_2, X_3)^{T}$ follows a multivariate normal distribution as $$ \mathbf{X} = (X_1, X_2, X_3)^\top \sim \mathcal N_3(\boldsymbol\mu, \Sigma), $$

with the mean vector

$$ \boldsymbol\mu = \begin{pmatrix} 259.5 \\ 230.8 \\ 221.5 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \Sigma = \begin{pmatrix} 2276 & 1508 & 813 \\ 1508 & 2206 & 1349 \\ 813 & 1349 & 1865 \end{pmatrix}. $$

We are interested in the difference between Day-4 and Day-0:

$$ Y = X_3 - X_1 = - X_1 + 0 X_2 + X_3 = \mathbf{c}^\top \mathbf{X}, \quad \text{where } \mathbf{c} = (-1, 0, 1)^\top. $$

What is the mean of this difference $Y$? What is the standard deviation of $Y$?

Solution: The mean (expected) difference

The mean of Y = the mean of X3 - the mean of X1 = -1 x the mean of X1 + 0 x the mean of X2 + 1 x the mean of X3 = -38.

or $ E Y $ = the mean of the difference $ = \sum_{j=1}^{p}c_j E(X_j) $ $ = -1 \times E(X_1) + 0 \times E(X_2) + 1 \times E(X_3) = -1 \times 259.5 + 0 \times 230.8 + 1 \times 221.5 $
$ = 221.5 - 259.5$ , which is $ E(X_3) - E(X_1) $ = -38.

$Var (Y) = Var(- X_1 + 0 X_2 + X_3 )$ , The varince = $\mathbf{c}^T \Sigma \mathbf{c}$

The problem can be solved using the code below:
